doc.source_uri: 2025-08-29/EM Weekly Kickstart MSCI EM fell 0.6 ww CEEMEA India lagged Liquidity-driven A-share rally continues We raised South Afr_2025-08-29

passages.text: Performance: MXEF fell - 0.6 w/w, dragged down by CEEMEA (- 2%) and India (- 2.3% w/w amid additional US tariffs), while Brazil led (+3.1% w/w).
Earnings/valuations: MXEF is trading at 13.3x NTM P/E (+1.1 s.d., 10- yr avg). 2025 EPS revision flat w/w. Egypt and Chile saw upgrades w/w, while Poland saw cuts.
Flows: EM equities saw selling of \(\) 3.0bn\(w/w, led by India\) (\text {\(- \S 0.8bn\)}) and Korea ( \(\) 0.7bn\(, while Brazil\) (\text {\(\) 0.1bn\)}) and Indonesia (\)\\(0.2bn\)\) saw inflows
Macro: Q2 GDP rose in India; Inflation fell in Poland; Philippines, Egypt cut rates, while Korea, Hungary remained on hold.

2Q results: About 918 out of 1202 MSCI EM companies (76% of Co's, 90% of market cap) have reported so far; 12% have beat EPS estimates by more than 1 s.d., 69% reported in line, while 19% missed by more than 1 s.d.
Focus: OW South Africa - Domestic rotation; A- share rally

OW South Africa: We raised South African equities to OW within EM, and expect further gains towards our 12- m target of 106,000 for the Top40 (JSE 40 index), which implies 12% local / 17% USD returns, driven by

mid- teen earnings growth next year. We expect further gains to be led by Domestics, which have lagged exporters by 60pp ytd (relative performance near 2- year lows) and trading inexpensive vs. their historical range, suggesting that Domestics are yet to price in our economists' view for a consumption driven cyclical growth recovery, and SARBs policy shift a lower inflation target - which should pay way lower rates. Within exporters, we prefer gold mine over PGMs as the rally in gold miners has been backed by earnings accrual and could extend even our commodities strategist positioned outlook for gold prices. On the other hand, PGMs appear vulnerable given valuation- led gains and a weaker outlook for earnings and PGM prices.

August performance / A- share rally: After 7 consecutive monthly gains ytd July, MSCI EM is +1.5% mtd in Aug. despite historically weak seasonality. The gains come amid dovish repricing of Fed expectations, continued inflows into EM equities and a rally in Chinese (A- share) equities amid retail liquidity- driven gains and anti- involution hopes for profit reflation. Our China strategists stay OW China and emphasize thematic alpha ideas over beta for better risk/reward.

Investors should consider this report as only a single factor in making their investment decision. For Reg AC certification and other important disclosures, see the Disclosure Appendix, or go to www.gs.com/research/hedge.html.
